Categorical data plots¶

If one of the main variables is categorical (divided into discrete groups) it may be helpful to use a more specialized approach to visualization.

Ref: https://seaborn.pydata.org/tutorial/categorical.html

Categorical plots belong in 3 different families:

  • Categorical estimate plots:

    • pointplot() (with kind="point")

    • barplot() (with kind="bar")

    • countplot() (with kind="count")

  • Categorical distribution plots:

    • boxplot() (with kind="box")

    • violinplot() (with kind="violin")

    • boxenplot() (with kind="boxen")

  • Categorical scatterplots:

    • stripplot() (with kind="strip"; the default)

    • swarmplot() (with kind="swarm")

avilable seaborn style are: darkgrid , whitegrid , dark , white , and ticks

In [2]:
import seaborn as sns 
%matplotlib inline

barplot and countplot¶

barplot is a general plot that allows to aggregate the categorical data based on some function, by default the mean.

In [4]:
sns.barplot(x='sex',y='total_bill',data=tips)
Out[4]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='sex', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [6]:
#adding estimator: Statistical function to estimate within each categorical bin. 
import numpy as np
sns.barplot(x='sex',y='total_bill',data=tips, estimator=np.std,palette='rainbow')
Out[6]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='sex', ylabel='total_bill'>

countplot¶

It is same as the barplot except the estimator is explicitly counting the number of occurrences. Hence we are going to pass only the x value.

In [18]:
sns.countplot(x='sex', data=tips)
Out[18]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='sex', ylabel='count'>
In [15]:
#Show point estimates and confidence intervals using scatter plot glyphs.
# avilable theme style: darkgrid , whitegrid , dark , white , and ticks
sns.set_theme(style='darkgrid')
sns.pointplot(x='sex',y='total_bill',data=tips)
Out[15]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='sex', ylabel='total_bill'>

boxplot and violin plot¶

  • boxplots and violinplots are used to shown the distribution of categorical data.

  • A box plot (or box-and-whisker plot) shows the distribution of quantitative data in a way that facilitates comparisons between variables or across levels of a categorical variable. The box shows the quartiles of the dataset while the whiskers extend to show the rest of the distribution, except for points that are determined to be "outliers" using a method that is a function of the inter-quartile range.

In [22]:
sns.boxplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,palette='cubehelix')
Out[22]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [25]:
#boxplot of entire dataframe with horizontal orientation 
sns.boxplot(data=tips,orient='h')
Out[25]:
<AxesSubplot:>
In [28]:
#Boxplot with hue 
sns.boxplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,hue='sex',palette='Spectral')
Out[28]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>

Violin plot¶

  • Draw a combination of boxplot and kernel density estimate.
  • A violin plot plays a similar role as a box and whisker plot.
  • Violin plot shows the distribution of quantitative data across several levels of one (or more) categorical variables such that those distributions can be compared
In [29]:
#sns.violinplot(x='day', y='total_bill', data=tips, palette='Spectral')
sns.violinplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,palette='Spectral')
Out[29]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [30]:
#violinplot with hue
sns.violinplot(x='day',y='total_bill',hue='sex',data=tips)
Out[30]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>

sns.violinplot(x='day',y='total_bill',hue='sex',data=tips,split=True)
Out[33]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [33]:

sns.violinplot(x='day',y='total_bill',hue='smoker',data=tips,split=True,palette='coolwarm')
Out[33]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>

stripplot and swarmplot¶

The stripplot draws a scatterplot where one variable is categorical. A strip plot can be drawn on its own, but it is also a good complement to a box or violin plot

In [35]:
sns.stripplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips)
Out[35]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [37]:
#stripplot with jitter set to False
sns.stripplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,jitter=False)
Out[37]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [47]:
#striplot with hue 
sns.set_theme(context='paper',style='white')
sns.stripplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,hue='sex',palette='Set1')
Out[47]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>
In [49]:
#striplot with hue an dodge (split) option to be set
sns.stripplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,hue='sex',dodge=True, palette='Set1')
Out[49]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day', ylabel='total_bill'>

catplot() with kind option¶

You can also use catplot() with kind option to create the above plots as well. It is generic version of creating different categorical plots by setting different kind option values.

In [66]:
#catplot with kind is bar
sns.catplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips, kind='bar')
Out[66]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fc9d89d0310>
In [69]:
#catplot with kind is strip
sns.catplot(x='day',y='total_bill',kind='strip',data=tips)
Out[69]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fc9eb926d90>
In [70]:
#catplot with kind is box
sns.catplot(x='day',y='total_bill',kind='box',data=tips)
Out[70]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fca0bfbe340>
In [74]:
#catplot with kind is box
sns.catplot(x='day',y='total_bill',kind='violin',data=tips,hue='sex',split=True)
Out[74]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fc9ec08e610>
